The margination of the mesosoma or its partial or complete loss is an important character, evident in a number of species that are intermediate between the dohrni-group, which includes species with a laterally marginate mesosomal dorsum and the porcata-group with a partly or completely immarginate condition. The transition is illustrated by the following series of species:
Polyrhachis exarata exarata & # 8594;
Polyrhachis planata planata & # 8594;
Polyrhachis sculpta sculpta & # 8594;
Polyrhachis excellens excellens & # 8594;
Polyrhachis porcata porcata & # 8594;
Polyrhachis orokana orokana & # 8594;
Polyrhachis geometrica geometrica & # 8594;
Polyrhachis decora decora . In the first species,
Polyrhachis exarata exarata , a member of the dohrni-group, the mesosoma is fully laterally and posteriorly, marginate. The second species, planata, still has complete lateral margins, but the posterior propodeal margins extend only partly towards the midline as short ridges. They fail to meet medially and there is a gap through which the dorsum meets the declivity. In
Polyrhachis sculpta sculpta , which could be considered intermediate between the dohrni- and porcata-group, the lateral margins of the mesosoma are less distinct posteriorly, leaving the propodeum only weakly marginate laterally and completely immarginate posteriorly. The margins of the mesosoma are incomplete in
Polyrhachis excellens excellens and related species, with the pronotal margins weak and extending from the pronotal spines for only part of the length of the pronotum. The margins merge with the outermost dorsal striae and curve onto the sides of pronotum, failing to reach the promesonotal suture. The mesonotal-propodeal dorsum is usually only partly marginate, leaving one or the other laterally immarginate. In
Polyrhachis porcata porcata there is only an indication of weak lateral margins of the mesosoma, with the propodeum terminating in barely distinct tubercles. The propodeum in orokana has a distinct transverse posterior margin, but the lateral margins of mesosoma are completely lost. A complex of species, represented in the series by
Polyrhachis geometrica geometrica , has the mesosoma virtually immarginate, although in some the outermost striae of the mesonotal dorsum form ill-defined lateral margins. Finally
Polyrhachis decora decora and its allies have the mesosoma completely immarginate.
